# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ipv6
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] An **Internet Protocol version 6 address** (**IPv6 address**) is a numeric label that is used to identify and locate a network interface of a computer or a network node participating in a computer network using IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] IP addresses are included in the packet header to indicate the source and the destination of each packet.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The IP address of the destination is used to make decisions about routing IP packets to other networks.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] IPv6 is the successor to the first addressing infrastructure of the Internet, Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4).
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] In contrast to IPv4, which defined an IP address as a 32-bit value, IPv6 addresses have a size of 128 bits.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Therefore, in comparison, IPv6 has a vastly enlarged address space.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] IPv6 addresses are classified by the primary addressing and routing methodologies common in networking: unicast addressing, anycast addressing, and multicast addressing.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] A unicast address identifies a single network interface.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The Internet Protocol delivers packets sent to a unicast address to that specific interface.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] An anycast address is assigned to a group of interfaces, usually belonging to different nodes.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] A packet sent to an anycast address is delivered to just one of the member interfaces, typically the nearest host, according to the routing protocol's definition of distance.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Anycast addresses cannot be identified easily, they have the same format as unicast addresses, and differ only by their presence in the network at multiple points.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Almost any unicast address can be employed as an anycast address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] A multicast address is also used by multiple hosts that acquire the multicast address destination by participating in the multicast distribution protocol among the network routers.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] A packet that is sent to a multicast address is delivered to all interfaces that have joined the corresponding multicast group.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] IPv6 does not implement broadcast addressing.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Broadcast's traditional role is subsumed by multicast addressing to the *all-nodes* link-local multicast group *ff02::1*.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] However, the use of the all-nodes group is not recommended, and most IPv6 protocols use protocol-specific link-local multicast groups to avoid disturbing every interface on a given network.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] For each of the major addressing and routing methodologies, various address formats are recognized by dividing the 128 address bits into bit groups and using established rules for associating the values of these bit groups with special addressing features.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Unicast and anycast addresses are typically composed of two logical parts: a 64-bit network prefix used for routing, and a 64-bit interface identifier used to identify a host's network interface.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The *network prefix* (the *routing prefix* combined with the *subnet ID*) is contained in the most significant 64 bits of the address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The size of the routing prefix may vary; a larger prefix size means a smaller subnet ID size.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The bits of the *subnet ID* field are available to the network administrator to define subnets within the given network.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The 64-bit *interface identifier* is automatically established randomly, obtained from a DHCPv6 server, or assigned manually.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Unique local addresses are addresses analogous to IPv4 private network addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The *prefix* field contains the binary value 1111110.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The *L* bit is one for locally assigned addresses; the address range with *L* set to zero is currently not defined.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The *random* field is chosen randomly once, at the inception of the */48* routing prefix.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] A link-local address is also based on the interface identifier, but uses a different format for the network prefix.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The *prefix* field contains the binary value 1111111010.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The 54 zeroes that follow make the total network prefix the same for all link-local addresses (*fe80::/64* link-local address prefix), rendering them non-routable.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Multicast addresses are formed according to several specific formatting rules, depending on the application.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] For all multicast addresses, the *prefix* field holds the binary value 11111111.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Currently, three of the four flag bits in the *flg* field are defined; the most-significant flag bit is reserved for future use.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The four-bit scope field (*sc*) is used to indicate where the address is valid and unique.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] In addition, the scope field is used to identify special multicast addresses, like solicited node.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The *sc(ope)* field holds the binary value 0010 (link-local).
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Solicited-node multicast addresses are computed as a function of a node's unicast or anycast addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] A solicited-node multicast address is created by copying the last 24 bits of a unicast or anycast address to the last 24 bits of the multicast address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Link-scoped multicast addresses use a comparable format.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] An IPv6 address is represented as eight groups of four hexadecimal digits, each group representing 16 bits The groups are separated by colons (:).
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The standards provide flexibility in the representation of IPv6 addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The full representation of eight four-digit groups may be simplified by several techniques, eliminating parts of the representation.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] In general, representations are shortened as much as possible.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] However, this practice complicates several common operations, namely searching for a specific address or an address pattern in text documents or streams, and comparing addresses to determine equivalence.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] These methods can lead to very short representations for IPv6 addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] During the transition of the Internet from IPv4 to IPv6, it is typical to operate in a mixed addressing environment.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] For such use cases, a special notation has been introduced, which expresses IPv4-mapped and IPv4-compatible IPv6 addresses by writing the least-significant 32 bits of an address in the familiar IPv4 dot-decimal notation, whereas the 96 most-significant bits are written in IPv6 format.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] For example, the IPv4-mapped IPv6 address *::ffff:c000:0280* is written as *::ffff:192.0.2.128*, thus expressing clearly the original IPv4 address that was mapped to IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] An IPv6 network uses an address block that is a contiguous group of IPv6 addresses of a size that is a power of two.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The leading set of bits of the addresses are identical for all hosts in a given network, and are called the network's address or routing *prefix*.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Network address ranges are written in CIDR notation.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] A network is denoted by the first address in the block (ending in all zeroes), a slash (/), and a decimal value equal to the size in bits of the prefix.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The routing prefix of an interface address may be directly indicated with the address using CIDR notation.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The size of a block of addresses is specified by writing a slash (/) followed by a number in decimal whose value is the length of the network prefix in bits.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] For example, an address block with 48 bits in the prefix is indicated by */48*.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Such a block contains 2128 − 48 = 280 addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The smaller the length of the network prefix, the larger the block: a */21* block is 8 times larger than a */24* block.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Colon (:) characters in IPv6 addresses may conflict with the established syntax of resource identifiers, such as URIs and URLs.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The colon is conventionally used to terminate the host path before a port number.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] where the trailing 443 is the example's port number.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] For addresses with other than global scope (as described in § Address scopes), and in particular for link-local addresses, the choice of the network interface for sending a packet may depend on which zone the address belongs to.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The same address may be valid in different zones, and in use by a different host in each of those zones.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Even if a single address is not in use in different zones, the address prefixes for addresses in those zones may still be identical, which makes the operating system unable to select an outgoing interface based on the information in the routing table (which is prefix-based).
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] In order to resolve the ambiguity in textual addresses, a *zone index* must be appended to the address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The zone index is separated from the address by a percent sign (%).
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Although numeric zone indices must be universally supported, the zone index may also be an implementation-dependent string.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The former (using an interface name) is customary on most Unix-like operating systems (e.g., BSD, Linux, macOS).
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The latter (using an interface number) is the only syntax on Microsoft Windows, but as support for this syntax is mandatory per standard, it is also available on other operating systems.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] BSD-based operating systems (including macOS) also support an alternative, non-standard syntax, where a numeric zone index is encoded in the second 16-bit word of the address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] In all operating systems mentioned above, the zone index for link-local addresses actually refers to an interface, not to a zone.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] As multiple interfaces may belong to the same zone (e.g. when connected to the same network), in practice two addresses with different zone identifiers may actually be equivalent, and refer to the same host on the same link.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] In Microsoft Windows operating systems, IPv4 addresses are valid location identifiers in Uniform Naming Convention (UNC) path names.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] However, the colon is an illegal character in a UNC path name.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Thus, the use of IPv6 addresses is also illegal in UNC names.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] For this reason, Microsoft implemented a transcription algorithm to represent an IPv6 address in the form of a domain name that can be used in UNC paths.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] For this purpose, Microsoft registered and reserved the second-level domain *ipv6-literal.net* on the Internet (although they gave up the domain in January 2014).
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] This notation is automatically resolved locally by Microsoft software, without any queries to DNS name servers.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Every IPv6 address, except the unspecified address (*::*), has a *scope*, which specifies in which part of the network it is valid.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] For unicast addresses, two scopes are defined: link-local and global.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Link-local addresses and the loopback address have *link-local* scope, which means they can only be used on a single directly attached network.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] All other addresses (including unique local addresses) have *global* (or *universal*) scope, which means they are potentially globally routable and can be used to connect to addresses with *global* scope anywhere, or to addresses with *link-local* scope on the directly attached network.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Unique local addresses have global scope, but they are not globally administered.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] As a result, only other hosts in the same administrative domain (e.g., an organization), or within a cooperating administrative domain are able to reach such addresses, if properly routed.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] As their scope is global, these addresses are valid as a source address when communicating with any other global-scope address, even though it may be impossible to route packets from the destination back to the source.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Anycast addresses are syntactically identical to and indistinguishable from unicast addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Their only difference is administrative.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Scopes for anycast addresses are therefore the same as for unicast addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] For multicast addresses, the four least-significant bits of the second address octet (*ff0s::*) identify the address scope, i.e. the domain in which the multicast packet should be propagated.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] All other scopes are unassigned and available to administrators for defining additional regions.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The management of IPv6 address allocation process is delegated to the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) by the Internet Architecture Board and the Internet Engineering Steering Group.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Its main function is the assignment of large address blocks to the regional Internet registries (RIRs), which have the delegated task of allocation to network service providers and other local registries.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The IANA has maintained the official list of allocations of the IPv6 address space since December 1995.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] In order to allow efficient route aggregation, thereby reducing the size of the Internet routing tables, only one-eighth of the total address space (*2000::/3*) is currently allocated for use on the Internet.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The rest of the IPv6 address space is reserved for future use or for special purposes.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The address space is assigned to the RIRs in blocks of */23* up to */12*.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The RIRs assign smaller blocks to local Internet registries that distribute them to users.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] These are typically in sizes from */19* to */32*.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Global unicast assignment records can be found at the various RIRs or other websites.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The addresses are then typically distributed in */48* to */56* sized blocks to the end users.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] In contrast, the entire IPv4 address space has only 232 (exactly 4,294,967,296; or about 4.3×109) addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] By design, only a small fraction of the address space will be used actively.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The large address space ensures that addresses are almost always available, which makes the use of network address translation (NAT) for the purposes of address conservation unnecessary.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] NAT has been increasingly used for IPv4 networks to help alleviate IPv4 address exhaustion.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Provider-independent address space is assigned directly to the end user by the RIRs from the special range (*2001:678::/29* for assignees in the RIPE NCC service region) and allows customers to make provider changes without renumbering their networks.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Internet exchange points (IXPs) are assigned special addresses from the ranges *2001:7f8::/32*, *2001:504::/30*, and *2001:7fa::/32* for communication with their connected ISPs.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The lowest address within each subnet prefix (the interface identifier set to all zeroes) is reserved as the *subnet-router* anycast address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Applications may use this address when talking to any one of the available routers, as packets sent to this address are delivered to just one router.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The 128 highest addresses within each */64* subnet prefix are reserved to be used as anycast addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] These addresses usually have the first 57 bits of the interface identifier set to 1, followed by the 7-bit anycast ID.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Prefixes for the network can be of any length for routing purposes, but subnets are required to have a length of 64 bits.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The address with value 0x7e in the 7 least-significant bits is defined as a mobile IPv6 home agents anycast address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The address with value 0x7f (all bits 1) is reserved and may not be used.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] No more assignments from this range have been made, so all the remaining values, 0x00 through 0x7d, are reserved as well.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] There are a number of addresses with special meaning in IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The IANA maintains a registry of these special-purpose addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Applications may listen on one or more specific interfaces for incoming connections, which are shown in listings of active internet connections by a specific IP address (and a port number, separated by a colon).
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] When the unspecified address is shown it means that an application is listening for incoming connections on all available interfaces.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] In routing table configuration, the unspecified address may be used to represent the default route address (corresponding to *0.0.0.0/0* in IPv4) for destination addresses (unicast, multicast and others) not specified elsewhere in a routing table.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] IANA has reserved a so-called *Sub-TLA ID* address block for special assignments of *2001::/23* (split into the range of 64 network prefixes *2001:0000::/29* through *2001:01f8::/29*).
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The multicast addresses *ff0x::*, where *x* is any hexadecimal value, are reserved and managed by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA).
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The least significant 24 bits of the solicited-node multicast address group ID are filled with the least significant 24 bits of the interface's unicast or anycast address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] These addresses allow link-layer address resolution via Neighbor Discovery Protocol (NDP) on the link without disturbing all nodes on the local network.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] A host is required to join a solicited-node multicast group for each of its configured unicast or anycast addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] On system startup, a node automatically creates a link-local address on each IPv6-enabled interface, even if globally routable addresses are manually configured or obtained through *configuration protocols* (see below).
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] It does so independently and without any prior configuration by **stateless address autoconfiguration** (**SLAAC**), using a component of the Neighbor Discovery Protocol.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] This address is selected with the prefix *fe80::/64*.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] In IPv4, typical *configuration protocols* include DHCP or PPP.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Newer IPv6 hosts can be configured to use the Neighbor Discovery Protocol to create a globally routable unicast address: the host sends router solicitation requests and an IPv6 router responds with a prefix assignment.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The lower 64 bits of the *fe80::/64* address are populated with a 64-bit interface identifier.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The globally unique and static MAC addresses used by stateless address autoconfiguration to create interface identifiers offer an opportunity to track user equipment across time and IPv6 network prefix changes.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] To reduce the prospect of a user identity being permanently tied to an IPv6 address portion, a node may create temporary addresses with interface identifiers based on time-varying random bit strings and relatively short lifetimes (hours to days), after which they are replaced with new addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Temporary addresses may be used as source addresses for originating connections, while external hosts use a public address by querying the Domain Name System (DNS).
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Network interfaces configured for IPv6 use temporary addresses by default in OS X Lion and later Apple systems as well as in Windows Vista, Windows 2008 Server and later Microsoft systems.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] As a means to enhance security for Neighbor Discovery Protocol *cryptographically generated addresses* (CGAs) were introduced in 2005 as part of the Secure Neighbor Discovery (SEND) protocol.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Such an address is generated using two hash functions that take several inputs.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The first uses a public key and a random modifier; the latter being incremented repeatedly until a specific amount of zero bits of the resulting hash is acquired.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The second hash function takes the network prefix and the previous hash value.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The least significant 64 bits of the second hash result is appended to the 64-bit network prefix to form a 128-bit address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The hash functions can also be used to verify if a specific IPv6 address satisfies the requirement of being a valid CGA.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] This way, communication can be set up between trusted addresses exclusively.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Modified EUI-64 also reduces the size of the address space for searching for attack targets.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Stable privacy addresses were introduced to remedy these shortcomings.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] They are stable within a specific network but change when moving to another, to improve privacy.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] They are chosen deterministically, but randomly, in the entire address space of the network.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Generation of a stable privacy address is based on a hash function that uses several stable parameters.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] It is implementation specific, but it is recommended to include at least the network prefix, the name of the network interface, a duplicate address counter, and a secret key.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The resulting hash value is used to construct the final address: Typically the 64 least significant bits are concatenated to the 64-bit network prefix, to yield a 128-bit address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] If the network prefix is smaller than 64 bits, more bits of the hash are used.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] If the resulting address does not conflict with existing or reserved addresses, it is assigned to the interface.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Conflicts are resolved by adjusting the duplicate address counter.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Each interface in SLAAC also has a solicited-node multicast address, formed from the network prefix *ff02::1:ff00:0/104* and the 24 least significant bits of its unicast or anycast address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] This multicast address is used in NDP to detect duplicate addresses and to establish the correspondence between IP addresses and link-layer (MAC) addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The use of non-hardware-derived addresses presents a possibility of duplicate addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The assignment of a unicast IPv6 address to an interface involves an internal test for the uniqueness of that address using *Neighbor Solicitation* and *Neighbor Advertisement* (ICMPv6 type 135 and 136) messages.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] While in the process of establishing uniqueness an address has a *tentative* state.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The node joins the *solicited-node* multicast address for the tentative address and sends neighbor solicitations, with the tentative address as the target address and the unspecified address (*::/128*) as its source address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The node also joins the all-hosts multicast address *ff02::1*, so it can receive *neighbor advertisements*.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] If a node receives a neighbor solicitation with its own tentative address as the target address, then it knows its address is not unique.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The same is true if the node receives a neighbor advertisement with the tentative address as the source of the advertisement.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Only after having successfully established that an address is unique may it be assigned and used by an interface.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] When an anycast address is assigned to an interface (e.g. a subnet-router anycast address), due to the inherent non-uniqueness of this type of address, duplicate address detection is not performed.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] In NDP the router also advertises what /64-sized prefix it has access to on the broader Internet as well as other network parameters.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] A node that receives this information joins the prefix with its own interface identifier to obtain its unicast address on the broader Internet.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] For example, if a router has access to *2001:db8:1:2::/64* and the machine has the interface identifier `02-0C-29-FF-FE-0C-47-D5` (continuing the above example), the machine would self-assign the address *2001:db8:1:2:020c:29ff:fe0c:47d5*.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] DHCPv6 remains useful for other purposes.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] For example, it can be used by the ISP's router to hand a /64-sized or shorter prefix to the customer's router, a process called prefix delegation.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Each IPv6 address that is bound to an interface has a defined lifetime.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Lifetimes are infinite, unless configured to a shorter period.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] There are two lifetimes that govern the state of an address: the *preferred lifetime* and the *valid lifetime*.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Lifetimes can be configured in routers that provide the values used for autoconfiguration, or specified when manually configuring addresses on interfaces.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] When an address is assigned to an interface it gets the status *preferred*, which it holds during its preferred-lifetime.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] After that lifetime expires the status becomes *deprecated* and no new connections *should* be made using this address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The address becomes *invalid* after its valid-lifetime also expires; the address is removed from the interface and may be assigned somewhere else on the Internet.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] IPv6-enabled network interfaces usually have more than one IPv6 address, for example, a link-local and a global address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] They may also have temporary addresses that change after a certain lifetime has expired.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] IPv6 introduces the concepts of address scope and selection preference, yielding multiple choices for source and destination addresses in communication with another host.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The preference selection algorithm selects the most appropriate address to use in communications with a particular destination, including the use of IPv4-mapped addresses in dual-stack implementations.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] It uses a configurable preference table that associates each routing prefix with a precedence level.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The default configuration places preference on IPv6 usage, and selects destination addresses within the smallest possible scope, so that link-local communication is preferred over globally routed paths when otherwise equally suitable.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The prefix policy table is similar to a routing table, with the (inverse) precedence value serving as the role of a link cost; larger values result in higher precedence.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Source addresses are preferred to have the same label value as the destination address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Addresses are matched to prefixes based on the longest-matching most-significant bit sequence.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Candidate source addresses are obtained from the operating system and candidate destination addresses may be queried via DNS.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] To minimize the time to establish a connection when multiple addresses are available for communication, the Happy Eyeballs algorithm was devised.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] It queries DNS for IPv6 and IPv4 addresses of the target host, sorts candidate addresses using the default address selection table, and tries to establish connections in parallel.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The first established connection aborts current and future attempts to connect to other addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] In the Domain Name System, hostnames are mapped to IPv6 addresses by *AAAA* resource records, so-called *quad-A* records.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] For reverse lookup the IETF reserved the domain ip6.arpa, where the name space is hierarchically divided by the 1-digit hexadecimal representation of nibble units (4 bits) of the IPv6 address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] As in IPv4, each host is represented in the DNS by two DNS records: an address record and a reverse mapping pointer record.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] For example, a host computer named *derrick* in zone *example.com* has the unique local address *fdda:5cc1:23:4::1f*.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] This pointer record may be defined in a number of zones, depending on the chain of delegation of authority in the zone d.f.ip6.arpa.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] The DNS protocol is independent of its transport layer protocol.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-address-p01] Queries and replies may be transmitted over IPv6 or IPv4 transports regardless of the address family of the data requested.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] To increase the deployment of IPv6 on the Internet, various transition mechanisms have been proposed to ease this process.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] Since IPv6 is not directly interoperable with its predecessor protocol IPv4, transition mechanisms are designed to permit hosts on either network type to communicate with any other host.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] To meet its technical criteria, IPv6 must have a straightforward transition plan from the current IPv4.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) conducts working groups and discussions through the IETF Internet Drafts and Request for Comments processes to develop these transition technologies toward that goal.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] Some basic IPv6 transition mechanisms are defined in RFC 4213.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] The specification is a product of the NGTRANS IETF working group, and was initially drafted in February 2000 by E.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] It was revised in 2011, and in 2016 its current revision was published.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] A tunnel broker provides IPv6 connectivity by encapsulating IPv6 traffic in IPv4 Internet transit links, typically using 6in4.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] This establishes IPv6 tunnels within the IPv4 Internet.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] The tunnels may be managed with the Tunnel Setup Protocol (TSP) or AYIYA.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] It is a mechanism to facilitate rapid deployment of the IPv6 service across IPv4 infrastructures of Internet service providers (ISPs).
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] It uses stateless address mappings between IPv4 and IPv6 addresses, and transmits IPv6 packets across automatic tunnels that follow the same optimized routes between customer nodes as IPv4 packets.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] It was used for an early large deployment of an IPv6 service with native addresses during 2007 (RFC 5569).
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] The standard-track specification of the protocol is in RFC 5969.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] The **Transport Relay Translation** (**TRT**) method acts as an intermediate device between two hosts.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] The function of the translator is to convert IPV6 into IPV4 addresses and vice versa.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] TRT accomplishes this translation through IP address mapping and a custom IP address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] The packets are routed toward the translator firstly through an IPv6/TCP protocol and then from the translator to the IPv4 host through an IPv4/TCP protocol.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] TRT employs a similar operation to DNS translation between AAAA and A records known as *DNS ALG*.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] NAT64 is a mechanism to allow IPv6 hosts to communicate with IPv4 servers.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] The NAT64 server is the endpoint for at least one IPv4 address and an IPv6 network segment of 32-bits, e.g., *64:ff9b::/96*.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] The IPv6 client embeds the IPv4 address with which it wishes to communicate using these bits, and sends its packets to the resulting address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] The NAT64 server then creates a NAT-mapping between the IPv6 and the IPv4 address, allowing them to communicate.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] NAT64 is typically used in conjunction with DNS64.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] ISATAP (Intra-Site Automatic Tunnel Addressing Protocol) is an IPv6 transition mechanism meant to transmit IPv6 packets between dual-stack nodes on top of an IPv4 network.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] Unlike 6over4 (an older similar protocol using IPv4 multicast), ISATAP uses IPv4 as a virtual nonbroadcast multiple-access network (NBMA) data link layer, so that it does not require the underlying IPv4 network infrastructure to support multicast.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] 464XLAT allows clients on IPv6-only networks to access IPv4-only Internet services.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] It extends NAT64 by adding another initial translation step from IPv4 to IPv6, which allows IPv4-only clients or applications to communicate over IPv6-only connections.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] The client uses a SIIT translator to convert packets from IPv4 to IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] These are then sent to a NAT64 translator which translates them from IPv6 back into IPv4 and on to an IPv4-only server.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] The client translator may be implemented on the client itself or on an intermediate device and is known as the CLAT (Customer-side transLATor).
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] RFC 7335 specifies a special IPv4 prefix *192.0.0.0/29* reserved by IANA for use in IPv4 transition scenarios, known as the *IPv4 Service Continuity Prefix*, which was previously reserved for specifically DS-Lite but has since been extended to support any transition mechanism similar in operation.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] The CLAT implementation may use addresses from this prefix for internal numbering, although packets containing these addresses are never actually sent out over the network.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] The NAT64 translator, or PLAT (Provider-side transLATor), must be able to reach both the server and the client (through the CLAT).
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] The PLAT is identical to standalone NAT64, and no changes need to be made from the provider side to support 464XLAT.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] The use of NAT64 limits connections to a client–server model using UDP, TCP, and ICMP.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] If DNS64 is in use on the IPv6-only network, most applications that need to connect to an IPv4-only service will already natively initiate connections using IPv6 to the NAT64 prefix.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] This means that 464XLAT is only required for applications that do not understand IPv6, have a preference for IPv4, or use hard-coded IPv4 addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] V4-via-v6 is defined for the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) and the Babel routing protocol.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] It has been implemented in the Bird Internet routing daemon and in *babeld*.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] Mapping of Address and Port (MAP) is a Cisco IPv6 transition proposal which combines A+P port address translation with tunneling of the IPv4 packets over an ISP provider's internal IPv6 network.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] MAP-T and MAP-E entered standards track in July 2015, and Sky Italia has deployed MAP-T in its internet services as early as year 2021.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] IPv4 Residual Deployment (4rd) is an experimental mechanism to facilitate residual deployment of the IPv4 service across IPv6 networks.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] Like 6rd, it uses stateless address mappings between IPv6 and IPv4.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] It supports an extension of IPv4 addressing based on transport-layer ports.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] This is a stateless variant of the A+P model.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] While almost identical to NAT-PT, *Network Address Port Translation + Protocol Translation*, which is also described in RFC 2766, adds translation of the ports as well as the address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] This is done primarily to avoid two hosts on one side of the mechanism from using the same exposed port on the other side of the mechanism, which could cause application instability and security flaws.
[src:ipv6/ipv6-transition-mechanism] This mechanism has been deprecated by RFC 4966.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Devices on the Internet are assigned a unique IP address for identification and location definition.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] With the rapid growth of the Internet after commercialization in the 1990s, it became evident that far more addresses would be needed to connect devices than the 4 billion (232) addresses IPv4 made available.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] By 1998, the IETF had formalized the successor protocol, IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] This uses 128-bit addresses, yielding an address space of 2128, 1038, or 340 undecillion total addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Several transition mechanisms have been devised to allow IPv4 and IPv6 to interoperate, but IPv6 is not backwards-compatible with IPv4 and the two do not interoperate directly.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv6 provides other technical benefits in addition to a larger addressing space.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In particular, it permits hierarchical address allocation methods that facilitate route aggregation across the Internet, and thus limit the expansion of routing tables.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The use of multicast addressing is expanded and simplified, and provides additional optimization for the delivery of services.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Device mobility, security, and configuration aspects have been considered in the design of the protocol.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv6 addresses are represented as eight groups of four hexadecimal digits each, separated by colons.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv6 is an Internet Layer protocol for packet-switched internetworking and provides end-to-end datagram transmission across multiple IP networks, closely adhering to the design principles developed in the previous version of the protocol, Internet Protocol Version 4 (IPv4).
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In addition to offering more addresses, IPv6 also implements features not present in IPv4.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] It simplifies aspects of address configuration, network renumbering, and router announcements when changing network connectivity providers.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] It simplifies packet processing in routers by placing the responsibility for packet fragmentation in the endpoints.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The IPv6 subnet size is standardized by fixing the size of the host identifier portion of an address to 64 bits.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The addressing architecture of IPv6 allows three different types of transmission: unicast, anycast and multicast.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv6 does not implement broadcast, and therefore has no notion of a broadcast address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Internet Protocol Version 4 (IPv4) was the first publicly used version of the Internet Protocol.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv4 was developed as a research project by the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA), a United States Department of Defense agency, before becoming the foundation for the Internet and the World Wide Web.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv4 includes an addressing system that uses numerical identifiers consisting of 32 bits.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] These addresses are typically displayed in dot-decimal notation as decimal values of four octets, each in the range 0 to 255, or 8 bits per number.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Thus, IPv4 provides an addressing capability of 232 or approximately 4.3 billion addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Address exhaustion was not initially a concern in IPv4 as this version was originally presumed to be a test of DARPA's networking concepts.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] During the first decade of operation of the Internet, it became apparent that methods had to be developed to conserve address space.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In the early 1990s, even after the redesign of the addressing system using a classless network model, it became clear that this would not suffice to prevent IPv4 address exhaustion, and that further changes to the Internet infrastructure were needed.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The last unassigned top-level address blocks of 16 million IPv4 addresses were allocated in February 2011 by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) to the five regional Internet registries (RIRs).
[src:ipv6/ipv6] At that point, each RIR still had available address pools and was expected to continue with standard address allocation policies until one */8* Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) block remained.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] After that, only blocks of 1,024 addresses (/22) were provided from the RIRs to a local Internet registry (LIR).
[src:ipv6/ipv6] RIPE NCC was the last to do so; it announced that it had fully run out of IPv4 addresses on 25 November 2019, and called for greater progress on the adoption of IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] On the Internet, data is transmitted in the form of network packets.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv6 specifies a new packet format, designed to minimize packet header processing by routers.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Because the headers of IPv4 packets and IPv6 packets are significantly different, the two protocols are not interoperable.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The main advantage of IPv6 over IPv4 is its larger address space.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The size of an IPv6 address is 128 bits, compared to 32 bits in IPv4.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The address space therefore has 2128 addresses (340 undecillion, approximately 3.4×1038).
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Some blocks of this space and some specific addresses are reserved for special uses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] While this address space is very large, it was not the intent of the designers of IPv6 to assure geographical saturation with usable addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Rather, the longer addresses simplify allocation of addresses, enable efficient route aggregation, and allow implementation of special addressing features.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In IPv4, complex Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) methods were developed to make the best use of the small address space.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The network identifier part of the address in IPv6 is usually 264 addresses, about four billion times the size of the entire IPv4 address space.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Thus, actual address space utilization will be small in IPv6, but network management and routing efficiency are improved by the large subnet space and hierarchical route aggregation.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Multicasting, the transmission of a packet to multiple destinations in a single send operation, is part of the base specification in IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In IPv4 this is an optional (although commonly implemented) feature.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv6 multicast addressing has features and protocols in common with IPv4 multicast, but also provides changes and improvements by eliminating the need for certain protocols.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv6 does not implement traditional IP broadcast, i.e. the transmission of a packet to all hosts on the attached link using a special *broadcast address*, and therefore does not define broadcast addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In IPv6, the same result is achieved by sending a packet to the link-local *all nodes* multicast group at address *ff02::1*, which is analogous to IPv4 multicasting to address *224.0.0.1*.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv6 also provides for new multicast implementations, including embedding rendezvous point addresses in an IPv6 multicast group address, which simplifies the deployment of inter-domain solutions.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In IPv4 it is very difficult for an organization to get even one globally routable multicast group assignment, and the implementation of inter-domain solutions is arcane.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Unicast address assignments by a local Internet registry for IPv6 have at least a 64-bit routing prefix, yielding the smallest subnet size available in IPv6 (also 64 bits).
[src:ipv6/ipv6] With such an assignment it is possible to embed the unicast address prefix into the IPv6 multicast address format, while still providing a 32-bit block, the least significant bits of the address, or approximately 4.2 billion multicast group identifiers.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Thus each user of an IPv6 subnet automatically has available a set of globally routable source-specific multicast groups for multicast applications.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv6 hosts configure themselves automatically.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Every interface has a self-generated link-local address and, when connected to a network, conflict resolution is performed and routers provide network prefixes via router advertisements.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Stateless configuration of routers can be achieved with a special router renumbering protocol.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] When necessary, hosts may configure additional stateful addresses via Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol version 6 (DHCPv6) or static addresses manually.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Like IPv4, IPv6 supports globally unique IP addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The design of IPv6 intended to re-emphasize the end-to-end principle of network design that was originally conceived during the establishment of the early Internet by rendering network address translation obsolete.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Therefore, every device on the network is globally addressable directly from any other device.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] A stable, unique, globally addressable IP address would facilitate tracking a device across networks.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Therefore, such addresses are a particular privacy concern for mobile devices, such as laptops and cell phones.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] To address these privacy concerns, the SLAAC protocol includes what are typically called "privacy addresses" or, more correctly, "temporary addresses".
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Temporary addresses are random and unstable.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] A typical consumer device generates a new temporary address daily and will ignore traffic addressed to an old address after one week.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Temporary addresses are used by default by Windows since XP SP1, macOS since (Mac OS X) 10.7, Android since 4.0, and iOS since version 4.3.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Use of temporary addresses by Linux distributions varies.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Renumbering an existing network for a new connectivity provider with different routing prefixes is a major effort with IPv4.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] With IPv6, however, changing the prefix announced by a few routers can in principle renumber an entire network, since the host identifiers (the least-significant 64 bits of an address) can be independently self-configured by a host.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The SLAAC address generation method is implementation-dependent.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IETF recommends that addresses be deterministic but semantically opaque.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Internet Protocol Security (IPsec) was originally developed for IPv6, but found widespread deployment first in IPv4, for which it was re-engineered.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] However, as of RFC 4301 IPv6 protocol implementations that do implement IPsec need to implement IKEv2 and need to support a minimum set of cryptographic algorithms.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] This requirement will help to make IPsec implementations more interoperable between devices from different vendors.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The IPsec Authentication Header (AH) and the Encapsulating Security Payload header (ESP) are implemented as IPv6 extension headers.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The packet header in IPv6 is simpler than the IPv4 header.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Many rarely used fields have been moved to optional header extensions.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The IPv6 packet header has simplified the process of packet forwarding by routers.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Although IPv6 packet headers are at least twice the size of IPv4 packet headers, processing of packets that only contain the base IPv6 header by routers may, in some cases, be more efficient, because less processing is required in routers due to the headers being aligned to match common word sizes.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] However, many devices implement IPv6 support in software (as opposed to hardware), thus resulting in very bad packet processing performance.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Additionally, for many implementations, the use of Extension Headers causes packets to be processed by a router's CPU, leading to poor performance or even security issues.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Moreover, an IPv6 header does not include a checksum.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The IPv4 header checksum is calculated for the IPv4 header, and has to be recalculated by routers every time the time to live (called hop limit in the IPv6 protocol) is reduced by one.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The absence of a checksum in the IPv6 header furthers the end-to-end principle of Internet design, which envisioned that most processing in the network occurs in the leaf nodes.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Integrity protection for the data that is encapsulated in the IPv6 packet is assumed to be assured by both the link layer or error detection in higher-layer protocols, namely the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) and the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) on the transport layer.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Thus, while IPv4 allowed UDP datagram headers to have no checksum (indicated by 0 in the header field), IPv6 requires a checksum in UDP headers.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv6 routers do not perform IP fragmentation.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv6 hosts are required to do one of the following: perform Path MTU Discovery, perform end-to-end fragmentation, or send packets no larger than the default maximum transmission unit (MTU), which is 1280 octets.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Unlike mobile IPv4, mobile IPv6 avoids triangular routing and is therefore as efficient as native IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv6 routers may also allow entire subnets to move to a new router connection point without renumbering.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The IPv6 packet header has a minimum size of 40 octets (320 bits).
[src:ipv6/ipv6] This provides the opportunity to extend the protocol in the future without affecting the core packet structure.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] However, RFC 7872 notes that some network operators drop IPv6 packets with extension headers when they traverse transit autonomous systems.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv4 limits packets to 65,535 (216 − 1) octets of payload.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] An IPv6 node can optionally handle packets over this limit, referred to as jumbograms, which can be as large as 4,294,967,295 (232 − 1) octets.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The use of jumbograms may improve performance over high-MTU links.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The use of jumbograms is indicated by the Jumbo Payload Option extension header.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] An IPv6 packet has two parts: a header and payload.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The header consists of a fixed portion with minimal functionality required for all packets and may be followed by optional extensions to implement special features.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The fixed header occupies the first 40 octets (320 bits) of the IPv6 packet.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] It contains the source and destination addresses, traffic class, hop count, and the type of the optional extension or payload which follows the header.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] This *Next Header* field tells the receiver how to interpret the data which follows the header.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] If the packet contains options, this field contains the option type of the next option.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The "Next Header" field of the last option points to the upper-layer protocol that is carried in the packet's payload.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The current use of the IPv6 Traffic Class field divides this between a 6 bit Differentiated Services Code Point. and a 2-bit Explicit Congestion Notification field.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Extension headers carry options that are used for special treatment of a packet in the network, e.g., for routing, fragmentation, and for security using the IPsec framework.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Without special options, a payload must be less than 64kB.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] With a Jumbo Payload option (in a *Hop-By-Hop Options* extension header), the payload must be less than 4 GB.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Unlike with IPv4, routers never fragment a packet.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Hosts are expected to use Path MTU Discovery to make their packets small enough to reach the destination without needing to be fragmented.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The design of the IPv6 address space implements a different design philosophy than in IPv4, in which subnetting was used to improve the efficiency of utilization of the small address space.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In IPv6, the address space is deemed large enough for the foreseeable future, and a local area subnet always uses 64 bits for the host portion of the address, designated as the interface identifier, while the most-significant 64 bits are used as the routing prefix.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] While the myth has existed regarding IPv6 subnets being impossible to scan, RFC 7707 notes that patterns resulting from some IPv6 address configuration techniques and algorithms allow address scanning in many real-world scenarios.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The 128 bits of an IPv6 address are represented in 8 groups of 16 bits each.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Each group is written as four hexadecimal digits (sometimes called *hextets* or more formally *hexadectets* and informally a *quibble* or *quad-nibble*) and the groups are separated by colons (:).
[src:ipv6/ipv6] As an IPv6 address may have more than one representation, the IETF has issued a proposed standard for representing them in text.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Because IPv6 addresses contain colons, and URLs use colons to separate the host from the port number, an IPv6 address used as the host-part of a URL should be enclosed in square brackets, e.g. http://[2001:db8:4006:812::200e] or http://[2001:db8:4006:812::200e]:8080/path/page.html.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] All interfaces of IPv6 hosts require a link-local address, which have the prefix *fe80::/10*.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] This prefix is followed by 54 bits that can be used for subnetting, although they are typically set to zeros, and a 64-bit interface identifier.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The host can compute and assign the Interface identifier by itself without the presence or cooperation of an external network component like a DHCP server, in a process called *link-local address autoconfiguration*.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The lower 64 bits of the link-local address (the suffix) were originally derived from the MAC address of the underlying network interface card.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] As this method of assigning addresses would cause undesirable address changes when faulty network cards were replaced, and as it also suffered from a number of security and privacy issues, RFC 8064 has replaced the original MAC-based method with the hash-based method specified in RFC 7217.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv6 uses a new mechanism for mapping IP addresses to link-layer addresses (e.g.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] MAC addresses), because it does not support the broadcast addressing method, on which the functionality of the Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) in IPv4 is based.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv6 implements the Neighbor Discovery Protocol (NDP, ND) in the link layer, which relies on ICMPv6 and multicast transmission.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv6 hosts verify the uniqueness of their IPv6 addresses in a local area network (LAN) by sending a neighbor solicitation message asking for the link-layer address of the IP address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] If any other host in the LAN is using that address, it responds.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] A host bringing up a new IPv6 interface first generates a unique link-local address using one of several mechanisms designed to generate a unique address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Should a non-unique address be detected, the host can try again with a newly generated address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Once a unique link-local address is established, the IPv6 host determines whether the LAN is connected on this link to any router interface that supports IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] It does so by sending out an ICMPv6 router solicitation message to the all-routers multicast group with its link-local address as source.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] If there is no answer after a predetermined number of attempts, the host concludes that no routers are connected.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] If it does get a response, known as a router advertisement, from a router, the response includes the network configuration information to allow establishment of a globally unique address with an appropriate unicast network prefix.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The assignment procedure for global addresses is similar to local-address construction.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The prefix is supplied from router advertisements on the network.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Multiple prefix announcements cause multiple addresses to be configured.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Stateless address autoconfiguration (SLAAC) requires a */64* address block.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Local Internet registries are assigned at least */32* blocks, which they divide among subordinate networks.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The initial recommendation of September 2001 stated assignment of a */48* subnet to end-consumer sites.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In March 2011 this recommendation was refined: The IETF "recommends giving home sites significantly more than a single */64*, but does not recommend that every home site be given a */48* either".
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Blocks of */56*s are specifically considered.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] It remains to be seen whether ISPs will honor this recommendation.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] For example, during initial trials, Comcast customers were given a single */64* network.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In the Domain Name System (DNS), hostnames are mapped to IPv6 addresses by AAAA ("quad-A") resource records.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] For reverse resolution, the IETF reserved the domain ip6.arpa, where the name space is hierarchically divided by the 1-digit hexadecimal representation of nibble units (4 bits) of the IPv6 address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] When a dual-stack host queries a DNS server to resolve a fully qualified domain name (FQDN), the DNS client of the host sends two DNS requests, one querying AAAA records and the other querying A records, in that order, by default.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] If both types of addresses are returned by the DNS, and there is a route for it, the IPv6 address is preferred over the IPv4 address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] However, the host operating system may be configured with an alternate preference for address selection.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] An alternative record type was used in early DNS implementations for IPv6, designed to facilitate network renumbering.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The *A6* resource record was used for the forward lookup, completed with a number of other innovations such as *bit-string labels* and *DNAME* records.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] After a discussion of the pros and cons of both schemes,) the use of A6 resource records has been deprecated to experimental status.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] IPv6 is not foreseen to supplant IPv4 instantaneously.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Both protocols will continue to operate simultaneously for some time.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Therefore, IPv6 transition mechanisms are needed to enable IPv6 hosts to reach IPv4 services and to allow isolated IPv6 hosts and networks to reach each other over IPv4 infrastructure.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] According to Silvia Hagen, a dual-stack implementation of the IPv4 and IPv6 on devices is the easiest way to migrate to IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Many other transition mechanisms use tunneling to encapsulate IPv6 traffic within IPv4 networks and vice versa.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] This is an imperfect solution, which reduces the maximum transmission unit (MTU) of a link and therefore complicates Path MTU Discovery, and may increase latency.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Dual-stack IP implementations provide complete IPv4 and IPv6 protocol stacks in the operating system of a computer or network device on top of the common physical layer implementation, such as Ethernet.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] This permits dual-stack hosts to participate in IPv6 and IPv4 networks simultaneously.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] A device with dual-stack implementation in the operating system has an IPv4 and IPv6 address, and can communicate with other nodes in the LAN or the Internet using either IPv4 or IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The DNS protocol is used by both IP protocols to resolve fully qualified domain names and IP addresses, but dual stack requires that the resolving DNS server can resolve both types of addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Such a dual-stack DNS server holds IPv4 addresses in the A records and IPv6 addresses in the AAAA records.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Depending on the destination that is to be resolved, a DNS name server may return an IPv4 or IPv6 IP address, or both.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] A default address selection mechanism, or preferred protocol, needs to be configured either on hosts or the DNS server.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The IETF has published Happy Eyeballs to assist dual-stack applications, so that they can connect using both IPv4 and IPv6, but prefer an IPv6 connection if it is available.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] However, dual-stack also needs to be implemented on all routers between the host and the service for which the DNS server has returned an IPv6 address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Dual-stack clients should be configured to prefer IPv6 only if the network is able to forward IPv6 packets using the IPv6 versions of routing protocols.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] When dual-stack network protocols are in place the application layer can be migrated to IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] While dual-stack is supported by major operating system and network device vendors, legacy networking hardware and servers do not support IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Internet service providers (ISPs) are increasingly providing their business and private customers with public-facing IPv6 global unicast addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] If IPv4 is still used in the local area network (LAN), however, and the ISP can only provide one public-facing IPv6 address, the IPv4 LAN addresses are translated into the public facing IPv6 address using NAT64, a network address translation (NAT) mechanism.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Some ISPs cannot provide their customers with public-facing IPv4 and IPv6 addresses, thus supporting dual-stack networking, because some ISPs have exhausted their globally routable IPv4 address pool.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Meanwhile, ISP customers are still trying to reach IPv4 web servers and other destinations.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] A significant percentage of ISPs in all regional Internet registry (RIR) zones have obtained IPv6 address space.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] This includes many of the world's major ISPs and mobile network operators, such as Verizon Wireless, StarHub Cable, Chubu Telecommunications, Kabel Deutschland, Swisscom, T-Mobile, Internode and Telefónica.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] While some ISPs still allocate customers only IPv4 addresses, many ISPs allocate their customers only an IPv6 or dual-stack IPv4 and IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] ISPs report the share of IPv6 traffic from customers over their network to be anything between 20% and 40%, but by mid-2017 IPv6 traffic still only accounted for a fraction of total traffic at several large Internet exchange points (IXPs).
[src:ipv6/ipv6] AMS-IX reported it to be 2% and SeattleIX reported 7%.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] A 2017 survey found that many DSL customers that were served by a dual stack ISP did not request DNS servers to resolve fully qualified domain names into IPv6 addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The survey also found that the majority of traffic from IPv6-ready web-server resources were still requested and served over IPv4, mostly due to ISP customers that did not use the dual stack facility provided by their ISP and to a lesser extent due to customers of IPv4-only ISPs.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The technical basis for tunneling, or encapsulating IPv6 packets in IPv4 packets, is outlined in RFC 4213.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] When the Internet backbone was IPv4-only, one of the frequently used tunneling protocols was 6to4.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Teredo tunneling was also frequently used for integrating IPv6 LANs with the IPv4 Internet backbone.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Teredo is outlined in RFC 4380 and allows IPv6 local area networks to tunnel over IPv4 networks, by encapsulating IPv6 packets within UDP.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The Teredo relay is an IPv6 router that mediates between a Teredo server and the native IPv6 network.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] It was expected that 6to4 and Teredo would be widely deployed until ISP networks would switch to native IPv6, but by 2014 Google Statistics showed that the use of both mechanisms had dropped to almost 0.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Hybrid dual-stack IPv6/IPv4 implementations recognize a special class of addresses, the IPv4-mapped IPv6 addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] These addresses are typically written with a 96-bit prefix in the standard IPv6 format, and the remaining 32 bits are written in the customary dot-decimal notation of IPv4.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Addresses in this group consist of an 80-bit prefix of zeros, the next 16 bits are ones, and the remaining, least-significant 32 bits contain the IPv4 address.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] A previous format, called "IPv4-compatible IPv6 address", was *::192.0.2.128*; however, this method is deprecated.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Because of the significant internal differences between IPv4 and IPv6 protocol stacks, some of the lower-level functionality available to programmers in the IPv6 stack does not work the same when used with IPv4-mapped addresses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Some common IPv6 stacks do not implement the IPv4-mapped address feature, either because the IPv6 and IPv4 stacks are separate implementations (e.g., Microsoft Windows 2000, XP, and Server 2003), or because of security concerns (OpenBSD).
[src:ipv6/ipv6] On these operating systems, a program must open a separate socket for each IP protocol it uses.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] On some systems, e.g., the Linux kernel, NetBSD, and FreeBSD, this feature is controlled by the socket option IPV6_V6ONLY.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The address prefix *64:ff9b::/96* is a class of IPv4-embedded IPv6 addresses for use in NAT64 transition methods.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] A number of security implications may arise from the use of IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Some of them may be related with the IPv6 protocols themselves, while others may be related with implementation flaws.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The addition of nodes having IPv6 enabled by default by the software manufacturer may result in the inadvertent creation of *shadow networks*, causing IPv6 traffic flowing into networks having only IPv4 security management in place.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] This may also occur with operating system upgrades, when the newer operating system enables IPv6 by default, while the older one did not.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Failing to update the security infrastructure to accommodate IPv6 can lead to IPv6 traffic bypassing it.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Shadow networks have occurred on business networks in which enterprises are replacing Windows XP systems that do not have an IPv6 stack enabled by default, with Windows 7 systems, that do.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Some IPv6 stack implementors have therefore recommended disabling IPv4 mapped addresses and instead using a dual-stack network where supporting both IPv4 and IPv6 is necessary.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Research has shown that the use of fragmentation could be leveraged to evade network security controls, similar to IPv4.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] As a result, it is now required that the first fragment of an IPv6 packet contains the entire IPv6 header chain, such that some very pathological fragmentation cases are forbidden.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Additionally, as a result of research on the evasion of RA-Guard, the use of fragmentation is deprecated with Neighbor Discovery, and discouraged with Secure Neighbor Discovery (SEND).
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Due to the anticipated global growth of the Internet, the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) in the early 1990s started an effort to develop a next generation IP protocol.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] By the beginning of 1992, several proposals appeared for an expanded Internet addressing system and by the end of 1992 the IETF announced a call for white papers.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In September 1993, the IETF created a temporary, ad hoc *IP Next Generation* (IPng) area to deal specifically with such issues.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The new area was led by Allison Mankin and Scott Bradner, and had a directorate with 15 engineers from diverse backgrounds for direction-setting and preliminary document review: The working-group members were J.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The Internet Engineering Task Force adopted the IPng model on 25 July 1994, with the formation of several IPng working groups.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] By 1996, a series of RFCs was released defining Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6), starting with RFC 1883.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The first RFC to standardize IPv6 was the RFC 1883 in 1995.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In 1998 RFC 2460 became the RFC for IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In July 2017 RFC 2460 was superseded by RFC 8200, which elevated IPv6 to "Internet Standard" (the highest maturity level for IETF protocols)..
[src:ipv6/ipv6] RFC 8201 is a related IPv6 standard that describes how to discover the most efficient network path from source to destination that has the largest packet size permitted to avoid IP packet fragmentation, and thus maintain packet transmission performance.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The 1993 introduction of Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) in the routing and IP address allocation for the Internet, and the extensive use of network address translation (NAT), delayed IPv4 address exhaustion to allow for IPv6 deployment, which began in the mid-2000s.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Universities were among the early adopters of IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Virginia Tech deployed IPv6 at a trial location in 2004 and later expanded IPv6 deployment across the campus network.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] By 2016, 82% of the traffic on their network used IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Imperial College London began experimental IPv6 deployment in 2003 and by 2016 the IPv6 traffic on their networks averaged between 20% and 40%.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] A significant portion of this IPv6 traffic was generated through their high energy physics collaboration with CERN, which relies entirely on IPv6.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The Domain Name System (DNS) has supported IPv6 since 2008.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In the same year, IPv6 was first used in a major world event during the Beijing 2008 Summer Olympics.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] By 2011, all major operating systems in use on personal computers and server systems had production-quality IPv6 implementations.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Cellular telephone systems presented a large deployment field for Internet Protocol devices as mobile telephone service made the transition from 3G to 4G technologies, in which voice is provisioned as a voice over IP (VoIP) service that would leverage IPv6 enhancements.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In 2009, the US cellular operator Verizon released technical specifications for devices to operate on its "next-generation" networks.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The specification mandated IPv6 operation according to the *3GPP Release 8 Specifications (March 2009)*, and deprecated IPv4 as an optional capability.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] The deployment of IPv6 in the Internet backbone continued.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In 2018 only 25.3% of the about 54,000 autonomous systems advertised both IPv4 and IPv6 prefixes in the global Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) routing database.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] A further 243 networks advertised only an IPv6 prefix.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Internet backbone transit networks offering IPv6 support existed in every country globally, except in parts of Africa, the Middle East and China.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] By mid-2018 some major European broadband ISPs had deployed IPv6 for the majority of their customers.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Sky UK provided over 86% of its customers with IPv6, Deutsche Telekom had 56% deployment of IPv6, XS4ALL in the Netherlands had 73% deployment and in Belgium the broadband ISPs VOO and Telenet had 73% and 63% IPv6 deployment respectively.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In the United States the broadband ISP Xfinity had an IPv6 deployment of about 66%.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] In 2018 Xfinity reported an estimated 36.1 million IPv6 users, while AT&T reported 22.3 million IPv6 users.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] As of June 2026, Google's statistics show that approximately 50% of users access Google services over IPv6 native connectivity.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] Adoption varies significantly by region, with countries such as India, France, and Germany reporting adoption rates exceeding 70%, while others lag behind.
[src:ipv6/ipv6] There is a peering dispute occurring between Hurricane Electric and Cogent Communications on IPv6, with the two network providers refusing to peer.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] The **Neighbor Discovery Protocol** (**NDP**), or simply **Neighbor Discovery** (**ND**), is a protocol of the Internet protocol suite used with Internet Protocol Version 6 (IPv6).
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] It operates at the internet layer of the Internet model, and is responsible for gathering various information required for network communication, including the configuration of local connections and the domain name servers and gateways.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] The protocol defines five ICMPv6 packet types to perform functions for IPv6 similar to the Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) and Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) Router Discovery and Router Redirect protocols for IPv4.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] It provides many improvements over its IPv4 counterparts.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] For example, it includes Neighbor Unreachability Detection (NUD), thus improving robustness of packet delivery in the presence of failing routers or links, or mobile nodes.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] The **Inverse Neighbor Discovery** (**IND**) protocol extension allows nodes to determine and advertise an IPv6 address corresponding to a given link-layer address, similar to Inverse ARP for IPv4.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] The Secure Neighbor Discovery Protocol (SEND), a security extension of NDP, uses Cryptographically Generated Addresses (CGA) and the Resource Public Key Infrastructure (RPKI) to provide an alternative mechanism for securing NDP with a cryptographic method that is independent of IPsec.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] Neighbor Discovery Proxy (ND Proxy) provides a service similar to IPv4 Proxy ARP and allows bridging multiple network segments within a single subnet prefix when bridging cannot be done at the link layer.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] NDP defines five ICMPv6 packet types for the purpose of router solicitation, router advertisement, neighbor solicitation, neighbor advertisement, and network redirects.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] Hosts inquire with Router Solicitation messages to locate routers on an attached link.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] Routers which forward packets not addressed to them generate Router Advertisements immediately upon receipt of this message rather than at their next scheduled time.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] Routers advertise their presence together with various link and Internet parameters either periodically, or in response to a Router Solicitation message.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] Neighbor solicitations are used by nodes to determine the link-layer address of a neighbor, or to verify that a neighbor is still reachable via a cached link-layer address.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] Neighbor advertisements are used by nodes to respond to a Neighbor Solicitation message, or unsolicited to provide new information quickly.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] Routers may inform hosts of a better first-hop router for a destination.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] IANA maintains a list of all current NDP options as they are published.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] Two computers, *A* and *B* are connected to the same local area network with no intervening gateway or router.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] *A* has a packet to send to IP address *2001:db8::55* which happens to be the address of *B*.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] *A* sends a neighbor solicitation message requesting an answer for *2001:db8::55* (destination *ff02::1:ff00:55* IP address and destination *33:33:FF:00:00:55* MAC address), which is accepted by *B* which is listening on its own solicited-node multicast address on the local network.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] *B* responds with a neighbor advertisement message containing its MAC and IP addresses.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] *A* receives the response and sends the packet on the link with *B's* MAC address.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] Typically, network nodes maintain a lookup cache that associates IP and MAC addresses.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] In this example, if A had the lookup cached, then it would not need to send the NDP request.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] Also, when B received the request, it could cache the lookup to A so that if B needs to send a packet to A later, it does not need to use NDP to lookup its MAC address.
[src:ipv6/neighbor-discovery-protocol] Finally, when A receives the NDP response, it can cache the lookup for future messages addressed to the same IP address.
